  <p>
    Passive fire protection (PFP) is the system of built-in, structural fire-safety measures that
    contain fire and smoke within a building — without any active intervention. A passive fire
    protection provider supplies, installs, and maintains these systems to keep buildings compliant
    and occupants safe.
  </p>

  <h2>Assessment of a Building</h2>

  <p>
    Before any passive fire protection work begins, a qualified provider will carry out a thorough
    assessment of the building. This assessment identifies:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>The current state of fire compartmentation (walls, floors, ceilings)</li>
    <li>The condition and compliance of fire doors and frames</li>
    <li>Penetrations where pipes, cables, or ducts pass through fire-rated elements</li>
    <li>Any gaps, breaches, or defects that could allow fire or smoke to spread</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The findings form the basis of a remediation plan, prioritised by risk level. Under the
    <strong>Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005</strong>, the responsible person for a
    non-domestic building is legally required to have a suitable and sufficient fire risk assessment
    in place — the building assessment carried out by a PFP provider directly supports this
    obligation.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Is Passive Fire Protection Necessary?</h2>

  <p>
    Buildings are divided into compartments — separate zones bounded by fire-rated walls, floors,
    and doors — to limit how far fire and smoke can spread. When these compartment boundaries are
    breached (by poorly fitted fire doors, unsealed penetrations, or damaged intumescent products),
    fire can travel rapidly through a building, reducing the time available for evacuation and
    putting lives at risk.
  </p>

  <p>
    Passive fire protection measures work automatically. There are no systems to trigger, no
    batteries to fail, and no human action required. They simply do their job — holding fire back
    long enough for occupants to escape and for the fire service to respond.
  </p>

  <p>Key passive fire protection measures include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fire-rated walls and floors</strong> — structural compartmentation that resists fire spread for defined periods (e.g., 30, 60, or 120 minutes)</li>
    <li><strong>Fire doors</strong> — certified doors and frames that maintain compartment integrity</li>
    <li><strong>Intumescent seals and strips</strong> — materials that expand under heat to seal gaps around doors and penetrations</li>
    <li><strong>Fire collars and sleeves</strong> — devices that seal around plastic pipes passing through fire-rated elements</li>
    <li><strong>Fire-stopping materials</strong> — products used to seal service penetrations in walls and floors</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Preventing Fires from Spreading</h2>

  <p>
    The primary role of a passive fire protection provider is to ensure fire cannot travel unchecked
    through a building. By maintaining the integrity of fire compartments, PFP measures give
    occupants the maximum possible time to evacuate safely and limit damage to the structure.
  </p>

